\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:introduction"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quality of commodities transacted within value chains,
 and the preservation of that quality throughout the chain,
 is central to value chain development 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "verhoogen2023firmlevel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Higher-quality inputs improve efficiency by yielding more output per unit of input and reducing waste 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bold2017lemon"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Maintaining quality during aggregation,
 storage,
 transport and processing is also critical for food safety and consumer health 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "hoffmann2023upside,hansman2020vertical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Beyond these direct effects,
 consistent quality fosters trust and reputation,
 supports compliance with domestic and export standards,
 and facilitates access to higher-value markets 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "atkin2017exporting,fieler2018trade"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As a result,
 the transformation of value chains is often accompanied by substantial quality upgrading,
 reshaping incentives and market structures 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "antras2013organizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For quality to become an important driver of behavior,
 actors must be properly incentivized to produce and preserve it.
 In many markets,
 such incentives take the form of price premiums for higher-quality products,
 which reward the additional effort or investment required to meet quality standards 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "shapiro1983premiums"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When buyers are willing and able to pay more for quality,
 producers have stronger incentives to adopt better inputs and practices,
 while intermediaries are more likely to safeguard quality during aggregation,
 storage,
 and transport 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bold2022market"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In the absence of such premiums,
 quality improvements may not be financially viable,
 and actors may instead prioritize volume over quality
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bai2025quality"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The emergence of quality premia is often hindered by difficulties in observing and verifying quality at the point of transaction.
 When quality attributes are not directly visible and are costly to discover,
 buyers face a classic problem of asymmetric information 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "akerlof1970lemons"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
 without credible verification mechanisms,
 high- and low-quality products trade at similar prices,
 eroding incentives to invest in quality and potentially producing adverse selection equilibria in which low-quality goods drive out high-quality ones.
 Aggregation across suppliers further weakens the connection between individual performance and observed quality,
 undermining incentives for improvement:
 Even when buyers wish to pay for quality,
 the absence of traceability prevents quality-enhancing investments from translating into higher returns.
 Further constraints arise from the coordination and investment required to establish quality-based payment systems,
 including grading,
 certification,
 and monitoring infrastructure.
 Even in settings where quality can be observed,
 the absence of systematic verification at the point of sale can prevent quality-based pricing from emerging
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bai2024quality"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aggregation across suppliers introduces a further and conceptually distinct impediment.
 When buyers observe only a group-level quality signal (as is common in commodity markets where grading,
 traceability,
 and individual branding are absent),
 the shared reputational stock of the aggregated pool functions as a common-pool resource.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tirole1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 shows,
 individual incentives are governed not only by one's own quality choices but by the group's aggregate track record,
 since individual contributions are observed only with noise;
 each producer can therefore free-ride on the group's standing by supplying below-optimal quality while transacting at the pool price.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "winfree2005collective"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 formalize this mechanism directly in agricultural markets,
 showing that without firm-level traceability,
 individual producers rationally extract from the collective reputational stock in a dynamic analogous to common-pool resource overuse,
 producing an equilibrium in which the group as a whole undersupplies quality even when a premium would be available to a verifiably high-quality producer.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This incentive-dilution logic is reinforced by the moral hazard in teams mechanism 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "holmstrom1982moral"
literal "false"

\end_inset

:
 when only aggregate output is contractible,
 no individual agent fully internalizes the returns to their effort,
 weakening quality investments at precisely the point where aggregation severs the link between individual performance and observed outcomes.
 The practical consequence is that even when buyers wish to pay for quality,
 the absence of traceability prevents quality-enhancing investments from translating into higher returns,
 a pattern well-documented empirically across commodity supply chains in developing countries 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bold2022market,minten2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Further constraints arise from the coordination and investment required to establish quality-based payment systems in the first place,
 including grading infrastructure,
 third-party certification,
 and monitoring capacity,
 each of which constitutes a public or collective good subject to its own underprovision problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The structure of the value chain itself can exacerbate these challenges.
 When producers and processors are linked only indirectly through layers of traders or informal intermediaries,
 the likelihood of traceability breaking down increases substantially 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bai2025quality,macchiavello2026quality"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 By contrast,
 in chains where producers are more directly connected to processors,
 opportunities for credible testing,
 traceability,
 and clearer communication of standards are greater,
 increasing the scope for effective quality-based incentives to emerge 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "bergquist2020competition"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These challenges are particularly salient in Uganda’s emerging dairy sub-sector.
 Over the past decade,
 the industry has undergone rapid transformation,
 especially in the southwestern milk shed around the city of Mbarara,
 where foreign direct investment has spurred the development of modern value chains 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "vancampenhout2021leading"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A dense network of milk cooling and collection centers (MCCs) now connects dairy farmers to a growing cluster of processors.
 In dairy,
 quality is central:
 it determines processing yields for products such as cheese,
 casein,
 and infant formula,
 and maintaining sanitary conditions is essential given the perishability of raw milk.
 Yet,
 despite this transformation,
 there is generally no functioning market for quality in Uganda;
 prices are typically fixed per liter,
 irrespective of compositional quality attributes such as butterfat,
 solids-not-fat,
 or protein content.
 Part of the explanation may lie in the lack of technological capacity to measure and communicate compositional quality at the point of aggregation.
 Most MCCs limit testing to freshness and basic adulteration checks,
 primarily for added water,
 and farmers rarely have access to test results.
 Without the ability to credibly observe and attribute quality at the farm level,
 the informational preconditions for quality-based pricing are simply absent,
 making it difficult to establish the kind of verification mechanism necessary for quality premia to emerge and sustain incentives along the chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use this setting to test whether strengthening quality observability can enable the emergence of quality premia in Uganda's dairy sector.
 We implement a cluster randomized controlled trial across four districts in the southwestern milk shed around Mbarara,
 randomly assigning 130 MCCs to receive milk analyzer equipment,
 digital record-keeping infrastructure,
 and farmer-facing quality information.
 Following a one-year intervention period,
 we measure outcomes at three levels.
 At the MCC level,
 we examine whether quality testing became embedded in routine operations (both for incoming farmer deliveries and outgoing sales to buyers) and whether this translated into higher prices or the emergence of explicit quality premiums on either side of the market.
 At the farmer level,
 we measure prices received and the incidence of quality bonuses.
 Finally,
 to obtain objective measures of compositional milk quality independent of self-reports,
 enumerators conducted supervised testing of all incoming milk deliveries at both treatment and control MCCs on a single day at endline,
 yielding direct measures of butterfat,
 solids-not-fat,
 protein,
 added water,
 and density across the full pool of active suppliers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intervention substantially increased the visibility,
 presence,
 and day-to-day use of quality-testing infrastructure,
 generating large and consistent increases in actual testing of both incoming and outgoing milk;
 the probability that an MCC tests incoming deliveries rose by over 50 percentage points relative to the control group.
 Despite this operational uptake,
 neither the MCC-level intervention nor the farmer-level information treatment affected prices or the emergence of quality premia at any stage of the chain:
 farmer sales prices,
 the incidence of quality bonuses,
 and all pricing outcomes at the MCC level were uniformly unresponsive,
 and no quality premiums materialized anywhere along the chain.
 Most importantly,
 analyzer installation improved milk quality itself (butterfat increased by around 0.11 percentage points,
 added water fell by nearly half a percentage point,
 and an overall quality index improved by roughly 0.2 standard deviations) while leaving biologically determined components such as SNF and protein unchanged.
 This pattern of effects,
 with adulteration falling but production-side attributes unchanged,
 is consistent with adjustments in handling and integrity rather than deeper shifts in feeding or animal management practices.
 Together,
 the results show that the intervention made quality observable and improved milk composition through reduced adulteration,
 but without corresponding changes in price incentives or widespread upstream behavioral upgrading:
 the market for quality did not materialize.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pattern of results (large increases in testing,
 measurable improvements in milk composition,
 yet no movement in prices) is consistent with a straightforward mechanism.
 The acceptance threshold MCCs apply to incoming milk functions as a floor:
 once quality measurement makes that floor credible and binding,
 adulteration falls and composition improves,
 but there is no incentive to invest beyond what is needed to clear it.
 The enforcement channel disciplines the bottom of the quality distribution without rewarding the top.
 Notably,
 the speed and consistency of the quality response suggests that the chain converges relatively quickly to this new equilibrium,
 one in which measurement has done its work,
 adulteration is curtailed,
 and behavior has adjusted.
 But it is a low-level equilibrium.
 The gains from quality measurement are real yet partial:
 value that could be unlocked through further investment in production practices,
 feeding,
 or handling remains uncaptured,
 because the price schedule offers no signal that such investment would be rewarded.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test whether activating the pricing channel can shift the chain to a higher equilibrium,
 we conduct a follow-up experiment at 19 MCCs where the measurement infrastructure is already operational,
 randomly assigning quality premiums to traders delivering milk to these MCCs.
 Treated traders receive UGX 100 per liter for each 0.1 percentage point of butterfat and solids-not-fat above East African standards,
 paid daily via mobile money.
 The experiment proceeds in two stages that jointly allow us to separate the contribution of rewards from the contribution of stricter enforcement to quality upgrading.
 In Stage 1,
 thresholds are set at the East African standards (3.3 percent fat and 8.5 percent SNF),
 coinciding with the rainy season when high-quality milk is naturally abundant and the premium tier is relatively accessible.
 In Stage 2,
 the fat threshold is raised from 3.3 to 3.9 percent,
 simulating the scarcity conditions of the dry season under which sourcing high-quality milk requires active effort from upstream suppliers.
 Together,
 the two stages trace how quality-linked contracts affect behavior both when the premium is within easy reach and when meeting it demands genuine investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The follow-up experiment reveals that injecting explicit quality premiums into the chain does shift trader behavior,
 but in ways that depend critically on the scarcity of high-quality milk.
 When quality thresholds are set at standard East African levels and high-quality milk is naturally abundant,
 treated traders respond primarily on the volume margin (daily deliveries increase by around 126 liters) without any meaningful improvement in fat content.
 Sourcing more of the milk already available is simply the most profitable response when quality is plentiful.
 When the fat threshold is raised and quality becomes scarce,
 the pattern shifts decisively:
 traders move from volume expansion to active quality-based sourcing,
 delivering milk with significantly higher fat content (up by around 0.17 percentage points),
 with SNF improving as well.
 The margin of adjustment changes when the margin that is rewarded changes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yet the most striking finding concerns price transmission.
 Despite receiving explicit,
 exogenously introduced quality premiums,
 treated traders do not pass value upstream to farmers;
 if anything,
 farm-gate prices move slightly downward,
 by around 17 UGX per liter.
 One plausible mechanism is that traders facing stronger incentives to source high-quality milk expand their supplier networks to increase the probability of meeting quality thresholds,
 and the resulting increase in the supply of potential sellers shifts bargaining power toward the trader.
 Alternatively,
 traders may substitute away from price-based competition for suppliers toward quality-based screening,
 spending more effort on selection and less on offering attractive prices.
 Whatever the mechanism,
 the result underscores the central finding of the paper:
 even when price incentives are injected into the chain,
 the structure of intermediation prevents them from reaching the farmers whose behavior ultimately determines raw milk quality at the source.
 Farmer feeding practices show some marginal improvement,
 but broader behavioral changes at the farm level do not survive to endline,
 likely reflecting the limited window over which upstream production decisions can adjust.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper contributes to three strands of literature.
 The first concerns the informational preconditions for quality-based markets.
 The theoretical framework motivating the intervention draws on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "akerlof1970lemons"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "tirole1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "winfree2005collective"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 all of which predict that the absence of credible quality measurement severs the link between individual effort and observed outcomes,
 generating pooling equilibria in which quality investment is socially suboptimal.
 A growing experimental literature explores how strengthening observability alters these equilibria.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "saenger2013contract"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show in the Vietnamese dairy sector that third-party verification of previously unobservable quality attributes substantially raises production intensity when embedded in a processor-run contract.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rao2023got"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 document that group-level quality incentives can overcome free-rider problems in Indian dairy cooperatives,
 though elite resistance to transparency limits their reach.
 Our study sharpens this literature by isolating the effect of observability from the effect of pricing:
 despite a large,
 credibly identified increase in testing intensity (the probability of testing incoming deliveries rising by over 50 percentage points),
 no quality premia materialized anywhere in the chain.
 This result establishes that observability is necessary but not sufficient for quality markets to emerge,
 and that the downstream contractual infrastructure linking observable quality to price differentials constitutes an independently binding constraint.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "xu2024farm"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 arrives at a closely related conclusion in Kenyan dairy cooperatives using a Bayesian traceability design:
 quality monitoring reduces adulteration through enforcement rather than through new price signals.
 Together,
 these studies suggest a recurring pattern in which measurement technology disciplines the lower tail of the quality distribution without activating the continuous quality gradient that higher-value markets require.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second,
 the paper contributes to the literature on quality incentive design,
 a question studied across several commodity settings.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "saenger2013contract"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find in the Vietnamese dairy sector that both penalties and bonuses improve farmer investment in quality-enhancing inputs,
 with bonuses generating the stronger response.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "macchiavello2019buyer"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 exploit the staggered rollout of a quality sustainability program in Colombian coffee and find that eligible farmers produced higher-quality output in response to embedded price premiums and extension services.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "treurniet2021potency"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 finds similarly in Indonesian dairy that individual quality incentives improve compositional quality quickly after introduction,
 though hygienic quality gains erode over time,
 suggesting that incentive effects may be fragile even when they successfully reach farmers.
 In a related setting,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "park2023quality"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 find that training dragon fruit farmers in Vietnam to meet export quality standards substantially increases quality,
 with effects amplified when accompanied by buyer incentives.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ashraf2009finding"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 among others,
 document that the structure of incentive contracts (in particular whether they reward effort or output) shapes the magnitude and margin of response.
 Our follow-up experiment,
 which exogenously introduces quality-linked payments to traders,
 provides direct evidence on how incentive structure interacts with the scarcity of the rewarded attribute:
 when quality thresholds are set at standard East African levels and high-quality milk is naturally abundant,
 treated traders expand volume without improving compositional quality;
 when the threshold is raised and quality becomes scarce,
 traders shift from volume expansion to active quality-based sourcing.
 This pattern maps cleanly onto the margin-of-adjustment logic in the contract theory literature (the behavioral response follows the margin that is actually rewarded) and connects to the broader argument in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "verhoogen2023firmlevel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that quality upgrading is fundamentally a margin-of-response problem shaped by the structure of incentives and input availability jointly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third,
 and most consequentially,
 the paper contributes to the literature on price transmission through intermediaries in agricultural value chains.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "casaburi2022individual"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 uses a randomized trader subsidy in the Sierra Leone cocoa chain and finds competitive pass-through to farmers,
 delivered either through prices or credit.
 Our follow-up experiment generates a sharply different result under otherwise similar experimental logic:
 traders receiving explicit,
 daily quality-linked bonuses paid via mobile money do not transmit value upstream;
 farm-gate prices if anything drift slightly downward,
 consistent with expanded sourcing shifting bargaining power toward traders.
 The contrast clarifies a mechanism:
 unconditional subsidies create competitive pressure that raises farmer prices,
 whereas quality-contingent premiums induce traders to expand supplier networks and screen for quality,
 responses that need not raise prices to any individual farmer.
 This distinction matters for how the literature interprets pass-through evidence and has direct implications for the design of quality-upgrading programs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bold2022market"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 document across four field experiments that even when downstream demand for quality exists,
 the organization of supply chains often prevents gains from reaching upstream producers;
 our experiment provides clean identification of the intermediation structure,
 rather than demand-side uncertainty or information frictions,
 as the relevant mechanism.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "minten2008"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offer complementary observational evidence that commodity chains in developing countries frequently fail to transmit quality signals upstream,
 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "fieler2018trade"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "antras2013organizing"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show theoretically that the organization of value chains shapes the incentive to invest in quality at each stage.
 We contribute experimental evidence that even when price incentives are cleanly injected at the intermediary level,
 the structure of intermediation can block their transmission to the farmers whose behavior determines raw material quality at the source.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally,
 the sequential two-experiment design speaks to a methodological contribution for research on value chain upgrading.
 Much of the existing literature studies either the informational or the pricing dimension of quality incentives,
 but rarely both in the same supply chain and with clean separation between them.
 By first varying observability in a large cluster-randomized trial and then varying pricing within an environment where measurement infrastructure is already operational,
 we can trace the binding constraint at each stage.
 The result (that measurement and pricing are complementary rather than substitutable,
 and that injecting incentives at the trader level does not propagate to farmers) points to a low-level equilibrium trap that cannot be escaped by addressing only one dimension of the problem.
 This sequential logic connects to the broader argument in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "verhoogen2023firmlevel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 that quality upgrading in developing-country value chains requires coordination across multiple margins simultaneously,
 and that partial interventions addressing only one bottleneck are likely to generate exactly the kind of limited,
 compliance-margin improvements documented here.
\end_layout

